-- 
Hungarian Stocks Drop to Six-Month Low on European Debt Concern

-- B y   Z o l t a n   S i m o n
-- 
2011-07-11T16:09:17Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-11/hungarian-stocks-drop-to-six-month-low-on-european-debt-concern.html
Hungary ’s benchmark stock index
dropped to the lowest in more than six months on concern that
 Europe ’s debt crisis may spread, and the forint weakened to a
record against the Swiss franc.  The BUX index retreated 2.2 percent to close at 21,815.8 at
5:06 p.m. in Budapest, the lowest closing level since Jan. 3.
Hungary’s currency slipped as much as 3.3 percent to a record-
low 228.58 per Swiss franc before trading at 227.58. OTP Bank
Nyrt., Hungary’s largest lender, fell 2.4 percent to 5,563
forint as the forint’s depreciation raises the risk of defaults
on mostly Swiss franc-denominated household mortgage loans.  European officials met today as speculation Italy may be
engulfed by the crisis and divisions on how to structure aid for
 Greece  sank stocks worldwide, dragging the Standard & Poor’s 500
Index to the biggest two-day drop since March, while Spanish 10-
year bond yields topped 6 percent for the first time since 1997.  Mol Nyrt., Hungary’s largest refiner, fell 2.3 percent to
20,170 forint.  Richter Gedeon Nyrt. (RICHT) , the country’s largest
drugmaker, dropped 2.4 percent to 36,900 forint.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Zoltan Simon in Budapest at 
